<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>The <Node id="4"/>Financial Services Authority<Node id="32"/>, the <Node id="38"/>City of London<Node id="52"/> regulator, has defended the decision of <Node id="93"/>Equitable Life<Node id="107"/>, the troubled insurer, not to reveal earlier <Node id="153"/>this year<Node id="162"/> that it was conducting a review of its bonus policy.<Node id="215"/>

<Node id="217"/>Holders of <Node id="228"/>Equitable<Node id="237"/>&apos;s with-profits policies were shocked to learn on <Node id="287"/>July 16<Node id="294"/> that as as result of the secret review, the board had decided to cut the value of their policies by up to <Node id="401"/>16 per cent<Node id="412"/>.<Node id="413"/>

<Node id="415"/>Richard Ottaway<Node id="430"/>, the shadow paymaster general, <Node id="462"/>last month<Node id="472"/> questioned the role of the <Node id="500"/>FSA<Node id="503"/> in the period after <Node id="524"/>Equitable<Node id="533"/> closed for new business last <Node id="563"/>December<Node id="571"/> until the pension fund cuts were announced.<Node id="615"/>

<Node id="617"/>In a letter to <Node id="632"/>Mr Ottaway<Node id="642"/> <Node id="643"/>last week<Node id="652"/>, <Node id="654"/>John Tiner<Node id="664"/>, managing director of the <Node id="691"/>FSA<Node id="694"/>&apos;s <Node id="697"/>Consumer, Investment and Insurance Directorate<Node id="743"/>, wrote: &quot;You will be aware that there have been further suggestions . . . that the <Node id="827"/>FSA<Node id="830"/> should have told policyholders about the fact that bonus policy was under review . . . Until the <Node id="928"/>Equitable<Node id="937"/> had completed the review and had some firm policy propositions to make, it is unclear what they (or we) could have told policyholders which would have put them in a better position to make a decision.<Node id="1138"/>

<Node id="1140"/>&quot;We are satisfied that as soon as the <Node id="1178"/>Equitable<Node id="1187"/> board made firm decisions, they announced them together with the steps they planned to take to inform policyholders of the consequences for them.&quot;<Node id="1334"/>

<Node id="1336"/>Mr Ottaway<Node id="1346"/> said: &quot;The <Node id="1358"/>FSA<Node id="1361"/> confirm they have powers to intervene but hint that they didn&apos;t consider it appropriate to do so. Given the sorry history of regulation as far as the <Node id="1512"/>Equitable<Node id="1521"/> is concerned this stance will be viewed by millions of policyholders with astonishment.&quot;<Node id="1610"/></TextWithNodes>
